<dl id="n54078j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54078j">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54078j"> 78(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> avoir le moine (bad luck) / bailler le moine / donner le / moine, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54078j"><li>FW 117.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n54078j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n54078j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54078j">MS BL 47476a-213</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:449 <a name="ed11" href="../../ff/fdra/eda.htm#ed11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed11.htm#n54078j">Draft: I.5&sect;1.11</a>/4.11</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[A train of misfortunes attach themselves to coming up against priests and monks &hellip; Hence the various expressions, <mark>&lsquo;to have the monk&rsquo;, &lsquo;to deal, or to give the monk to someone&rsquo;</mark>, all meaning to invite and confer misfortune.]</font> <small> L. Sainean, <a name="LSLR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LSLR"><cite title="source">La Langue de Rabelais</cite></a> (1922) I (Superstitions) 311</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
